As we begin the Gorilla Football season, please help us ensure our athletes can continue with their season by following the Governor‚Äôs Executive Order for face coverings and practice social distancing.

UIL requires schools to ensure proper social distancing, limiting game capacity to 50%. Bleachers will be marked off to follow social distancing guidelines. Please respect the barriers and keep 6 feet between your group and those not of your household. This includes seating near the concession stand.

UIL published a letter to Superintendents and ADs Wednesday, tightening expectations. Schools not following these guidelines are subject to sanctions or discontinuation of public access to games by the local DEC/UIL State Executive Committee.

All guests assume the responsibility and risk for their individual health care choices. However, PLEASE SUPPORT our youth and their efforts to compete by not jeopardizing their season.

Thank you for supporting the Trent Gorillas.

The expectations of tonight's 7:00 ZOOM meeting shall include but not limited to the following, in no order:
*All positive comments/opinions/ideas will be welcome
*Comments that are not appropriate, if addressed, will take valuable time away from the business at hand.
*This will not be a decision making meeting. I will need time to explore the ideas and see what I can legally do.
*Decisions will hopefully be very quick
*If this ZOOM is helpful I am good with making this a regular event. Feedback is very helpful.
We have set up an email that you can use to ask your questions. It is important that we make the conversations as transparent as possible.
Our planning sessions are not secret meetings. The address is tisd-questions@trent.esc14.net
I would like to keep this meeting to an hour or less to honor your duties but if we are not through we will continue as long as needed or until our ZOOM minutes run out.
I am looking forward to our time together tonight.
Be Safe!!!!!!!

I realize that having young children going to school, perhaps for the first time, is a very anxious time for parents. I am exploring ideas that we can utilize and still meet the recommended school building safety requirements.
I would like to offer an opportunity for positive input concerning this issue as well as other circumstances and questions that parents would like to discuss.
I will host a ZOOM meeting Tomorrow night at 7:00 pm for all individuals that want to make positive suggestions/comments.
I will post the details on how to join the meeting this afternoon afternoon.

It is for these reasons that Trent ISD‚Äôs high school graduation had to be a a closed ceremony with guests permitted by invitation only. 2020 SENIOR SPOTLIGHT

Jordan R Luckie

Jordan's plans after graduation is to attend ACU to study Kinesiology. He wants to become an orthopedic surgeon.

What advice would you give next year's seniors?
I would tell them to always push through the hard times because the reward is well worth it at the end.

What will you miss most about Trent High School?
I will miss all the relationships and memories, good and bad, I had with all the teachers and my fellow students.It's hard to say I am fixing to graduate but the journey must come to an end at some time.

TRENT SENIOR SPOTLIGHT

Kaylee J Scheets

Kaylee wants to get her CNA through Cisco College; then continue working toward her RN.

What advice would you give next year's seniors?
senioritis- a supposed affliction of students in their final year of high school characterized by a decline in motivation or performance. You will feel this more than anything thought the year just please don't give up because I doesn't last as long as you wish it would!

What will you miss most about Trent ISD?
What I will miss most from high school is getting to see my teachers and friends each and everyday even though sometimes I didn't want to, and also I will miss all of the memories I made because Lord knows most of them meant embarrassing myself

post_text:
Trent ISD Staff Stories....
And just like that, the teachers became the students. Trent teachers and staff hit the ground running when they returned from Spring Break 2020!! In the wake of the world wide pandemic, our teachers put on their creative caps to figure out how best to educate our students in new ways. In an effort to help with the transition, teachers taught teachers how to create and use Google Classroom, how to use Zoom, and how to create and manage their own teacher webpages. All of our paraprofessional staff including our maintenance crew, piled into the computer lab to earn their ‚ÄúFood Handling‚Äù certificates so they could help with student meals. The selflessness I‚Äôve seen, the long hours, the way they‚Äôve helped each other for the sake of our students, has been inspiring and heart warming to witness. I‚Äôm very proud of this bunch, and thankful to work alongside these everyday heroes. Some call them faculty members, but I prefer the title ‚ÄúEducational Rockstars!‚Äù Thank you Trent ISD Faculty and Staff!! Go Gorillas!!
#MakingItWorkInTheJungle!!

post_text:
Gotta Brag: Our designer for our new website wrote this to me (Our yearbook kids all our photos):

I've spent a good deal of time on your website thus far today. A lot of it can't be seen visually as it's related to accessibility adjustments, but it's been useful time. The items that can be seen visually...let me just say, I can't believe how amazing your district's photography is. I've been in the industry for over a decade, and this is the most amazing amount of pleasure I've had from handling a district's photographs. Very incredible! It's taken a quite some time choosing what images would be great in the homepage slider. Really, almost every single photograph you uploaded is perfect, so it's been a day of very hard decisions. Please feel free to disagree on any! I've placed five images on display for the homepage, though I do wish I could have displayed more.

post_text:
Trent would like to welcome another new teacher to our community and school. Please welcome Ashley Dennes

"Hey there, name is Ashley Dennes and I am so excited for my first year at Trent! This is my second year teaching and my first year teaching middle school. Previously, I taught 4th grade in Austin and coached middle school volleyball. I was raised as a military brat, so I don't really have a place that I call home. In high school and college I played volleyball, basketball, soccer, and cheered for a competitive squad. In my free time, I love to go to the gym, teach Zumba, and hang out by the pool or lake. This year I will be teaching 6th, 7th, and 8th grade Reading and Writing and coaching High School cheer. I am looking forward to what the next school year will bring. Go Gorillas!"
